          <long_desc isprivate="0">
            <who name="Scott Adkins">adkinss@ohio.edu</who>
            <bug_when>2003-07-24 14:53:30 EDT</bug_when>
            <thetext>In sieve/addr-lex.c and sieve/sieve-lex.c, there are two lines each that have 
#pragma indented slightly (has a leading space).  This works fine in GCC and a 
lot of compilers, but I have run into compilers where this will fail to compile. 
 Removing the leading space solves the problem.</thetext>
          </long_desc>
          <long_desc isprivate="0">
            <who name="Scott Adkins">adkinss@ohio.edu</who>
            <bug_when>2003-07-24 14:54:40 EDT</bug_when>
            <thetext>Created an attachment (id=208)
Portability fix to #pragma

Removes the leading space in front of the #pragma directives for portability in
compiling on non-gcc oriented compilers.</thetext>
          </long_desc>
          <long_desc isprivate="0">
            <who name="Rob Siemborski">rjs3@andrew.cmu.edu</who>
            <bug_when>2003-07-24 14:55:34 EDT</bug_when>
            <thetext>Hmmm,

is

# pragma

an ok substitute?

we use

# define
in a lot of places.</thetext>
          </long_desc>
          <long_desc isprivate="0">
            <who name="Scott Adkins">adkinss@ohio.edu</who>
            <bug_when>2003-07-24 14:59:41 EDT</bug_when>
            <thetext>Yeah, there is no problem with having white space between the # and the 
directive.  The only requirement is that the # character be in the very first 
position of the line.  The following is fine:

#ifndef SOMETHING
#   pragma Blah
#   include &lt;header&gt;
#endif</thetext>
          </long_desc>
          <long_desc isprivate="0">
            <who name="Rob Siemborski">rjs3@andrew.cmu.edu</who>
            <bug_when>2003-07-24 15:47:44 EDT</bug_when>
            <thetext>Actually, both of these files are generated by lex.  It&apos;s (unfortuinately for
us), not a cyrus bug per se (its a bug in the code generated by lex)

Sigh, this sort of thing sucks.</thetext>
          </long_desc>
      
